HEADWORD: Gorse
<hw>Gorse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. & AS.
<ets>gorst</ets>; perh. akin to E. <ets>grow</ets>,
<ets>grass</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Furze. See
<er>Furze</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The common, overgrown with fern, and rough⟦br⟧
With prickly <qex>gorse</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gorse bird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the European
linnet; -- called also <altname>gorse hatcher</altname>.</cd>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>Gorse chat</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the winchat.</cd> -- <col><b>Gorse
duck</b></col>, <cd>the corncrake; -- called also <altname>grass
drake</altname>, <altname>land drake</altname>, and <altname>corn
drake</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gory</ent>⟦br⟧
